{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511765"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:44:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:44:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11776"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11776"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.05,0.08,0.46,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4389"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113212"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4389"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2022-05-10T16:00:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-10T13:33:52+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2023-06-30T20:59:38+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-22 10:52:00"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11776"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"4395"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95239"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"4459"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6383"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9177"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9357"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17066"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34500"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46070"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95239"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113212"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman (G2P2) has just given birth to a healthy baby boy in hospital following induction of labour for gestational hypertension. She undergoes an actively managed third stage without complication and subsequent examination of the placenta shows it to be intact. A minor tear of the perineum is currently being repaired. The midwife suturing the perineum notes that there appears to be more blood than expected on the pads on the bed. She asks for them to be weighed, and they are found to weigh 1200 g together. She has no significant medical history, does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 95/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.6\u0000B0C. The midwife carefully inspects the perineum and vagina and does not see any additional injuries. Previous blood results show no coagulopathies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate medication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ergometrine","Misoprostol","Blood products","Oxytocin","Carboprost"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe blood loss is almost certainly uterine in origin and related to poor tone. \u003Cstrong\u003EOxytocin \u003C/strong\u003Eadministered intravenously is the most appropriate initial medical management of primary postpartum haemorrhage (PPH) caused by poor uterine tone, even if it has already been administered for management of the third stage of labour (when it is typically administered intramuscularly). Local guidelines vary according to the dose and formulation. It is essential that non-pharmacological management of PPH is also undertaken, namely emptying the maternal bladder, fundal rub and/or bimanual compression. In addition to uterotonics, other aspects of early management include prompt fundal massage and administration of tranexamic acid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranexamic acid\u003C/strong\u003E may be used to manage prolonged bleeding in a PPH following the use of oxytocin and ergometrine. It would not be given as the initial medical management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Emisoprostol\u003C/strong\u003E has been used in routine management of the third stage of labour, quality trials in the hospital setting have reported that it is less effective than oxytocin and is associated with a greater incidence of side effects, for example: nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea, vaginal irritation and low grade fever. User familiarity and the efficacy of oxytocin make it the more appropriate option in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is essential to replace platelets and clotting factors with \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood products\u003C/strong\u003E in severe PPH, however it would not be the initial medical management for this patient. \u0022Point of Care\u0022 testing (e.g. ROTEM) can be used to guide the use of blood products in PPH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarboprost\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered a second line medication for the management of PPH. Although it is a potent uterotonic, it has a more serious side effect profile.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErgometrine\u003C/strong\u003E is a uterotonic sometimes used in PPH, but it is relatively contraindicated in people with hypertensive disorders of pregnancy due to the risk of precipitating hypertension, coronary spasm and stroke. Given this birth followed induction for gestational hypertension, ergometrine would not be the immediate choice.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Oxytocin is the initial medical management of a primary postpartum haemorrhage caused by lack of uterine tone."],"references":["NSW Health. Postpartum Haemorrhage (PPH) [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www1.health.nsw.gov.au/pds/ActivePDSDocuments/GL2021_017.pdf","RANZCOG. Management of Postpartum Haemorrhage (PPH). 2021. Available at: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Management-Postpartum-Haemorrhage.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95239"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11776"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95239"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-10T13:26:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-10T13:33:44+09:30","number":13,"notes":"Updated the explanation only: added explicit note that early management also includes fundal massage and administration of tranexamic acid; revised the discussion of ergometrine to emphasise contraindication in hypertensive disorders of pregnancy such as gestational hypertension. No other sections were changed.","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-09-10T13:33:15+09:30","plagiarismScore":0,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-4389-13.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T031457Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=53b8624805db328e81895a7a47bf1618590e5c0a0449a7cbb8855cd3f0008b2d"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4389"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113212"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"generation":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisionGenerations","id":"24815"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":